Title : William L. Adams (pioneer)
Text : '''William Lysander Adams''' (1821 – 1906) was an American writer, newspaper editor, and doctor from [[Oregon]].<ref name=Cogswell>{{cite book |last= Cogswell, Jr. |first= Philip |title= Capitol Names: Individuals Woven Into Oregon's History |publisher = [[Oregon Historical Society]] |year= 1977 |location= Portland, Oregon |pages=92–93}}</ref>

==Early life and career==
Adams was born in [[Oberlin, Ohio]] on February 5, 1821.<ref name=Republican>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=6j8QAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA171 |title= Republican League Register of Oregon |publisher= The Register Publishing Company |year= 1896 |pages= 171–172}}</ref> He came to [[Yamhill County, Oregon|Yamhill County]], Oregon in 1848.<ref name=Cogswell/> He worked as a teacher and made two trips to the [[California Gold Rush|California gold fields]] before publishing the play ''Treason, Strategems<!--[sic]-->, and Spoils, A [[Melodrame]] in Five Acts'' under the pen name '''Breakspear''' in 1852.<ref name=Cogswell/> The play, a political satire that skewered the Democratic party, including [[Asahel Bush]] and his ''[[Statesman Journal|Salem Statesman]]'', was first printed in ''[[The Oregonian]]'', and is often cited along with [[Margaret Jewett Bailey]]'s ''The Grains'' as one of the earliest works of literature written in Oregon.<ref name=Cogswell/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ohs.org/education/oregonhistory/narratives/subtopic.cfm?subtopic_ID=134 |title= Person and Place Wedded Together |publisher= Oregon Historical Society |accessdate= April 26, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Literature>{{cite web |url= http://www.oregonencyclopedia.org/articles/oregon_literature_1814_1920_/ |title= Oregon Literature (1814–1920) |publisher= [[The Oregon Encyclopedia]] |last= Etulain |first= Richard |accessdate= April 26, 2014}}</ref>

In 1855, Adams bought the ''[[Oregon Spectator]]'' and renamed it the ''[[Oregon City Argus|Oregon Argus]]''.<ref name=Cogswell/> The [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig]] newspaper, published in [[Oregon City, Oregon|Oregon City]], became politically influential in the late [[Oregon Territory|territorial]] period.<ref name=Cogswell/> Adams left the newspaper business and studied medicine in [[Philadelphia]], later practicing medicine in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] and [[Hood River, Oregon|Hood River]].<ref name=Cogswell/><ref name=Republican/>

==Family and legacy==
William L. Adams is one of the 158 names of people important to Oregon's history that are painted in the House and Senate chambers of the [[Oregon State Capitol]].<ref name=Cogswell/> Adams' name is in the [[Oregon House of Representatives|House]] chamber.

Adams' younger brother, [[Sebastian C. Adams]] (1825 – 1898), was an [[Oregon State Senate|Oregon State Senator]] and writer, best known for publishing a popular illustrated history chart.<ref name=Green>{{cite web |url= http://www.oregonencyclopedia.org/articles/adams_sebastian_c_1825_1898_/ |last= Green |first= Virginia |publisher= [[The Oregon Encyclopedia]] |title= Sebastian C. Adams (1825–1898) |accessdate= April 26, 2014}}</ref>

